A 21-YEAR-OLD suspect is expected to appear in court for allegedly killing two schoolkids after his taxi lost control. It’s alleged that on Friday, 4 February the suspect was drunk while ferrying the children. He lost control of his taxi and it collided with a truck on the R103 Old Main Road in Pietermaritzburg. KZN police spokeswoman Lieutenant-Colonel Nqobile Gwala said two children aged 10 and 14 were declared dead at the scene. “A 21-year-old suspect was placed under arrest. He will appear in the Howick Magistrates Court on Monday, 7 January,” said Gwala. KZN Education MEC Kwazi Mshengu has called for harsh action to be taken against the driver after two school children were killed and six injured in a road accident involving a minibus that was ferrying school children. According to preliminary reports, the schoolkids were on their way from school when a minibus taxi they were travelling in lost control and rammed into a truck and turned over. Two pupils were declared dead at the scene, and six sustained serious injuries and were taken to nearby hospitals for medical attention. “Witnesses said the driver of the minibus taxi was visibly drunk when the accident took place. He was arrested immediately and will appear in court on Monday. Local police said an investigation has been launched into the accident,” said Mshengu. The MEC sent his heartfelt condolences to the friends and family of the dead, wished the injured pupils a speedy recovery.